    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Currently every plugin is `git clone`d into '~/.local/share/nvim/site/pack/core/opt' and managed assuming it is a local copy of some remote repository. This allows the following useful assumptions:\n- All plugins managed by `vim.pack` are located only in one specific directory.\n- All plugins in one specific directory are managed only by `vim.pack`.\n\nThere were suggestions to add support for so called \"local plugins\" (as \"unmanaged plugins\" in 'vim-plug'). The idea is to allow to load plugins from any local path but not manage them at all. I.e. something like this:\n- `vim.pack.add('~/my-plugins/plugin1')` adds the path to 'runtimepath' and executes 'plugin/' / 'after/plugin/' files.\n- `vim.pack.update()` and `vim.pack.del()` don't know/care about such plugins.\n\nMy personal preference is that suggesting to manually add such plugins is okay. For example, by putting such plugins in '~/.local/share/nvim/site/pack/mine/start' or '.../mine/opt' and manually call `:packadd`.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> The idea is to allow to load plugins from any local path but not manage them at all. I.e. something like this:\n\ngit already supports `file:///` URIs. What's missing from that? The fact that `vim.pack` does a \"clone\" from the `file:///` URI seems completely fine, AFAICT. Why is it worth extra logic and surface area to support a different flavor?\n\n> * `vim.pack.add('~/my-plugins/plugin1')` adds the path to 'runtimepath' and executes 'plugin/' / 'after/plugin/' files.\n\n`vim.pack.add('file:///home/foo/my-plugins/plugin1')` already works.\n\n> * `vim.pack.update()` and `vim.pack.del()` don't know/care about such plugins.\n\nupdate/del already work with `file:///`.\n\nIt might require the user to `git init` in the local dir. That's a totally fine constraint.",
